# CSS Animation Fill-Mode Requirements

## Critical Rule: Always Specify Fill-Mode for Timeline Animations

When creating CSS animations for Editframe elements (ef-text, ef-image, ef-video, ef-timegroup, etc.), you **MUST** specify the appropriate `animation-fill-mode` to prevent flashing/flickering issues.

## Why This Matters

Editframe's timeline system:
1. Pauses all CSS animations
2. Manually controls them via `animation.currentTime`
3. Elements exist in the DOM **before** their animations start

Without proper fill-mode, elements will "flash" to their natural state before/after animations, creating jarring visual glitches.

## Required Fill-Mode Patterns

### Pattern 1: Delayed Animations â†’ Use `backwards`

**Problem:** Element shows natural state during delay, then suddenly jumps when animation starts.

```css
/* âťŚ WRONG - Will flash during 500ms delay */
animation: fade-in 1s 500ms;

/* âś… CORRECT - Shows initial keyframe during delay */
animation: fade-in 1s 500ms backwards;
```

**Rule:** Any animation with a delay MUST use `backwards` or `both`.

### Pattern 2: Fade-In / Slide-In Effects â†’ Use `backwards`

**Problem:** Element visible in natural state before animation begins.

```css
/* âťŚ WRONG - Element visible at opacity: 1 before fading in */
@keyframes fade-in {
  from { opacity: 0; }
  to { opacity: 1; }
}
.element {
  animation: fade-in 1s;
}

/* âś… CORRECT - Element hidden (opacity: 0) until animation starts */
.element {
  animation: fade-in 1s backwards;
}
```

**Rule:** Fade-in, slide-in, scale-in, and similar entrance effects MUST use `backwards` or `both`.

### Pattern 3: Fade-Out / Slide-Out Effects â†’ Use `forwards`

**Problem:** Element snaps back to natural state after animation completes.

```css
/* âťŚ WRONG - Element becomes visible again after fading out */
@keyframes fade-out {
  from { opacity: 1; }
  to { opacity: 0; }
}
.element {
  animation: fade-out 500ms;
}

/* âś… CORRECT - Element stays hidden (opacity: 0) after animation */
.element {
  animation: fade-out 500ms forwards;
}
```

**Rule:** Fade-out, slide-out, and similar exit effects MUST use `forwards` or `both`.

### Pattern 4: Sequential/Staggered Animations â†’ Use `backwards`

**Problem:** Elements in a sequence flash before their turn.

```html
<!-- âťŚ WRONG - Each element flashes during its delay -->
<ef-text style="animation: fade-in 1s 0s">First</ef-text>
<ef-text style="animation: fade-in 1s 500ms">Second</ef-text>
<ef-text style="animation: fade-in 1s 1s">Third</ef-text>

<!-- âś… CORRECT - Elements hidden until their animation starts -->
<ef-text style="animation: fade-in 1s 0s backwards">First</ef-text>
<ef-text style="animation: fade-in 1s 500ms backwards">Second</ef-text>
<ef-text style="animation: fade-in 1s 1s backwards">Third</ef-text>
```

**Rule:** Staggered animations MUST use `backwards` or `both`.

### Pattern 5: Combined In/Out Effects â†’ Use `both`

**Problem:** Element flashes at both start and end.

```css
/* âťŚ WRONG - Flashes at start AND end */
animation: 
  fade-in 1s,
  fade-out 500ms calc(var(--ef-duration) - 500ms);

/* âś… CORRECT - Applies both initial and final states */
animation: 
  fade-in 1s backwards,
  fade-out 500ms calc(var(--ef-duration) - 500ms) forwards;

/* âś… ALSO CORRECT - Single animation with both */
animation: fade-in-out 2s both;
```

**Rule:** Animations with both entrance and exit effects MUST use `both`, or specify `backwards` and `forwards` separately.

## Common Animation Patterns

### Fade In
```css
@keyframes fade-in {
  from { opacity: 0; }
  to { opacity: 1; }
}
.element {
  animation: fade-in 1s backwards; /* or 'both' */
}
```

### Fade Out
```css
@keyframes fade-out {
  from { opacity: 1; }
  to { opacity: 0; }
}
.element {
  animation: fade-out 500ms forwards; /* or 'both' */
}
```

### Slide In
```css
@keyframes slide-in-left {
  from { transform: translateX(-100%); }
  to { transform: translateX(0); }
}
.element {
  animation: slide-in-left 800ms backwards; /* or 'both' */
}
```

### Slide Out
```css
@keyframes slide-out-right {
  from { transform: translateX(0); }
  to { transform: translateX(100%); }
}
.element {
  animation: slide-out-right 500ms forwards; /* or 'both' */
}
```

### Scale/Zoom In
```css
@keyframes zoom-in {
  from { transform: scale(0); }
  to { transform: scale(1); }
}
.element {
  animation: zoom-in 600ms backwards; /* or 'both' */
}
```

### Combined Entrance and Exit
```css
.element {
  animation: 
    fade-in 1s backwards,
    fade-out 500ms calc(var(--ef-duration) - 500ms) forwards;
}
```

## Real-World Example

From the card-poetry template:

```html
<ef-timegroup
  mode="contain"
  style="
    animation:
      fadein 1250ms backwards,
      fadeout 500ms calc(var(--ef-duration) - 500ms) forwards;
  "
>
  <h1 style="animation: 1s slide-in-left ease-out backwards">
    9 of Spades
  </h1>
  <ef-image
    src="/assets/card.png"
    style="
      animation-composition: add;
      animation:
        4s rotate 4s,
        1s slide-in-left 0.25s ease-out backwards;
    "
  />
</ef-timegroup>
```

## Quick Reference Table

| Animation Type | Fill-Mode | Reason |
|---------------|-----------|---------|
| Fade-in | `backwards` or `both` | Hide element before animation |
| Slide-in | `backwards` or `both` | Position element before animation |
| Scale-in | `backwards` or `both` | Size element before animation |
| Fade-out | `forwards` or `both` | Keep element hidden after animation |
| Slide-out | `forwards` or `both` | Keep element positioned after animation |
| With delay | `backwards` or `both` | Apply initial state during delay |
| Combined in/out | `both` | Apply both initial and final states |

## Development Mode Validation

The Editframe system includes automatic validation in development mode that will warn you if:
- An animation has a delay but no `backwards`/`both` fill-mode
- A fade-in animation lacks `backwards`
- A fade-out animation lacks `forwards`
- Transform animations lack proper fill-mode

Check your browser console for warnings like:
```
đźŽ¬ Editframe Animation Fill-Mode Warning
âš ď¸Ź  Animation "fade-in" has a 500ms delay but no 'backwards' fill-mode.
   Fix: Add 'backwards' or 'both' to the animation shorthand.
   Example: animation: fade-in 1000ms 500ms backwards;
```

## When in Doubt

If you're unsure which fill-mode to use, `both` is the safest choice:

```css
/* Safe default for most animations */
animation: my-animation 1s both;
```

## Technical Background

CSS animations have four fill-mode values:
- `none` (default): No styles applied before/after animation
- `forwards`: Final keyframe styles persist after animation
- `backwards`: Initial keyframe styles applied before animation starts
- `both`: Combination of forwards and backwards

Editframe's timeline system requires explicit fill-modes because:
1. Elements are rendered before their timeline position
2. Animations are paused and controlled manually
3. Without fill-mode, browsers apply natural element styles instead of keyframe styles

